                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1552">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.51/71.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">French Chargé d’Affaires</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1361.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 1, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your note of July 23d, with which you enclose a copy of a report, dated July
                    15th, from the French Consular Agent at El Paso, Texas, covering the treatment
                    of the Christian Brothers of the Zacatecas School, at the hands of the
                    Constitutionalists.</p>
                <p>In reply you are informed that the Department has sent copies of this report to
                    its special representatives in Mexico, for their information in connection with
                    future representations they may be called upon to make in behalf of the
                    Christian Brothers.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
